WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.375 --> 00:00:03.458
(light bright music)

2
00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:09.570
<v ->We are going to switch gears</v>

3
00:00:09.570 --> 00:00:12.295
and do the first of two presentations

4
00:00:12.295 --> 00:00:15.526
on women's health to get through everything.

5
00:00:15.526 --> 00:00:18.030
I still have nothing to disclose.

6
00:00:18.030 --> 00:00:19.890
Here are our learning objectives,

7
00:00:19.890 --> 00:00:21.840
and we're going to start with the discussion

8
00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:23.220
of abnormal uterine bleeding,

9
00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.500
which remember is menstrual flow outside

10
00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:30.500
of either normal volume, regularity or frequency.

11
00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:32.617
Now normally it's simply a disruption

12
00:00:32.617 --> 00:00:35.100
of the normal physiology.

13
00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:37.050
So there at the top, you're at the pituitary.

14
00:00:37.050 --> 00:00:39.840
The FSH is what's going to induce ovarian follicles.

15
00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:42.090
They produce estrogen.

16
00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:44.380
The estrogen is like fertilizer

17
00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:48.690
for the endometrium and it promotes growth.

18
00:00:48.690 --> 00:00:52.203
The LH surge will then prompt the ovulation.

19
00:00:53.700 --> 00:00:55.170
The result in corpus lutetium,

20
00:00:55.170 --> 00:00:56.790
once you have your ovulation,

21
00:00:56.790 --> 00:00:58.800
is what is going to secrete progesterone.

22
00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:01.860
And that's gonna be important for stabilizing that

23
00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:05.370
lush lawn that you've developed inside the endometrium.

24
00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:08.315
And then in the absence of a pregnancy,

25
00:01:08.315 --> 00:01:11.280
the estrogen and progesterone fall

26
00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:14.220
and you get rid of all of that lining.

27
00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:15.390
Now most people think,

28
00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:16.740
oh my gosh, I'm gonna bleed to death.

29
00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:18.030
And I understand that.

30
00:01:18.030 --> 00:01:19.320
But actually, in any cycle,

31
00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:21.840
only about 80 CCs of blood is lost.

32
00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:24.690
Most of this, of course, is going to be tissue.

33
00:01:24.690 --> 00:01:25.950
Let's start with this question.

34
00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:28.959
A 39-year-old G2P2, she presents for follow-up.

35
00:01:28.959 --> 00:01:30.330
She was seen two weeks ago

36
00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:33.453
with a complaint of 13 months of infrequent periods.

37
00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:36.810
Otherwise healthy, non-smoker, no medications,

38
00:01:36.810 --> 00:01:39.840
breastfed both of her children for more than 12 months.

39
00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:42.030
The oldest child is 10.

40
00:01:42.030 --> 00:01:45.120
Vitals are normal, BMI is 24.8.

41
00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:46.980
Her physical exam was in normal limits

42
00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:48.120
including the pelvic exam.

43
00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:49.860
The most recent Pap was 11 months ago.

44
00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:54.780
Negative for an intraepithelial lesion, HPV negative.

45
00:01:54.780 --> 00:01:56.220
Urine pregnancy test is negative.

46
00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:59.760
A serum TSH and prolactin are within normal limits.

47
00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:01.503
So here is the question.

48
00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:05.068
Which one of the following

49
00:02:05.068 --> 00:02:08.043
is the best initial approach in this patient?

50
00:02:09.390 --> 00:02:11.070
Now as you're answering this question,

51
00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:14.223
remember it doesn't say, what would you do?

52
00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:20.043
It says of the following, which is the best, okay?

53
00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:29.580
Okay, and 52, 51% of you chose the correct answer.

54
00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:32.340
You would prescribe a 35 microgram ethinyl estradiol

55
00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:34.187
combination contraceptive pill daily.

56
00:02:34.187 --> 00:02:37.920
Here you want to use a monophasic pill.

57
00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:41.910
Now, what's the diagnosis here?

58
00:02:41.910 --> 00:02:43.653
We've got anovulatory bleeding.

59
00:02:45.150 --> 00:02:48.450
So we've got a lot of estrogen on board,

60
00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:50.820
insufficient progesterone to stabilize the endometrium.

61
00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:52.050
And you basically your endometrium

62
00:02:52.050 --> 00:02:53.403
outgrows its blood supply.

63
00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:59.089
Now, if you have abnormal uterine bleeding and ovulatory,

64
00:02:59.089 --> 00:03:02.370
this is irregular or infrequent periods,

65
00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:05.433
your progesterone deficient, estrogen dominant.

66
00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:10.320
The issue here is that the estrogen

67
00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:12.150
is the gasoline, unfortunately,

68
00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.519
which will potentially increase your risk

69
00:03:14.519 --> 00:03:17.343
for hyperplasia and then dysplasia.

70
00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:20.220
Now what are the commonly associated terms here?

71
00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:22.527
I could have amenorrhea, I could oligomenorrhea,

72
00:03:22.527 --> 00:03:25.193
I could metrorrhagia, or I could have DUB.

73
00:03:26.070 --> 00:03:29.133
Ovulatory is where I have regular cycles.

74
00:03:29.970 --> 00:03:32.010
I'm not bleeding between them.

75
00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:35.820
However, there's a change in the menstrual products.

76
00:03:35.820 --> 00:03:39.150
Either I am having excessive amounts,

77
00:03:39.150 --> 00:03:43.620
clots or some of my patients call 'em clogs.

78
00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:45.697
I'm like, "You've got clogs coming out?"

79
00:03:45.697 --> 00:03:47.787
"Yeah, Dr. Weismiller, big clogs."

80
00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:52.353
But they also vomit.

81
00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:57.360
Okay, very heavy periods

82
00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:00.030
or the duration is greater than eight days.

83
00:04:00.030 --> 00:04:01.983
Now let's start with anovulatory.

84
00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:06.753
If you are an adolescent,

85
00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:12.483
it's secondary to an immature hypothalamic-pituitary axis.

86
00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:17.790
The other end of the cycle, which is perimenopause,

87
00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:19.743
is the other big differential.

88
00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:23.040
If you're not one of those,

89
00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:25.980
any other time it's gonna be considered abnormal.

90
00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:28.050
And what do we gotta be thinking about?

91
00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:29.700
Well, do they have uncontrolled diabetes?

92
00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:30.780
Is there an eating disorder?

93
00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:32.190
Do they have a thyroid disorder?

94
00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:34.260
Is there a prolactinoma?

95
00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:36.720
Are they on a medication they can cause this?

96
00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:41.310
Do they have PCOS and are they pregnant?

97
00:04:41.310 --> 00:04:44.043
Dr. Weismiller, it's impossible for me to be pregnant.

98
00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:45.980
Well, you're pregnant.

99
00:04:47.670 --> 00:04:49.023
Well, how'd that happen?

100
00:04:49.857 --> 00:04:53.520
(students laughing)

101
00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:55.710
Here's the evaluation.

102
00:04:55.710 --> 00:04:58.290
You always do a pregnancy test.

103
00:04:58.290 --> 00:04:59.677
You know, I have residents come in and they'll say,

104
00:04:59.677 --> 00:05:01.080
"Yeah, I'm gonna send somebody to wherever."

105
00:05:01.080 --> 00:05:04.530
I'm like, "Have you done a pregnancy test?"

106
00:05:04.530 --> 00:05:05.460
Oh, I didn't think about that.

107
00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:07.770
Okay, pregnancy test, CBC,

108
00:05:07.770 --> 00:05:10.530
gotta look for thyroid disorder and prolactin.

109
00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:13.563
Now, 45 is the new 35.

110
00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:17.950
If they are over than 45

111
00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:21.990
and I've got anovulatory bleeding in a patient

112
00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:26.160
where I cannot say this is a normal physiologic event,

113
00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:29.310
then they're gonna need some type of evaluation,

114
00:05:29.310 --> 00:05:31.560
i.e. an endometrial biopsy.

115
00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:33.570
Because what am I looking for?

116
00:05:33.570 --> 00:05:36.510
Hyperplasia, potentially dysplasia.

117
00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:38.820
If they're under 45,

118
00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.045
where am I concerned about that hyperplasia, dysplasia?

119
00:05:41.045 --> 00:05:43.020
Well, they've got chronic anovulation,

120
00:05:43.020 --> 00:05:44.130
they have diabetes.

121
00:05:44.130 --> 00:05:45.750
There's a family history of colon cancer

122
00:05:45.750 --> 00:05:47.670
'cause that's a question of Lynch syndrome.

123
00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:48.870
They're infertile.

124
00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:51.150
They have null parity, obese, tamoxifen,

125
00:05:51.150 --> 00:05:54.093
all these things which drive estrogen up.

126
00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:57.480
More fuel on the fire.

127
00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:01.140
So if they're an adolescent or if I'm under 45

128
00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:03.360
and there's not a risk factor for endometrial cancer,

129
00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:05.070
and we'll look at that in just a second,

130
00:06:05.070 --> 00:06:06.660
then they get long-term medical therapy.

131
00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:08.643
And any of those can be used.

132
00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:12.570
Any of those can be used there.

133
00:06:12.570 --> 00:06:14.700
Now if they don't respond,

134
00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:17.350
those are the patients who get an endometrial biopsy.

135
00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:19.500
If the results are normal,

136
00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:20.450
they get a transvaginal ultrasound

137
00:06:20.450 --> 00:06:23.073
'cause they need to look for structural abnormality.

138
00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:26.880
If the etiology is still unclear,

139
00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:28.680
they're gonna go for a hysteroscopy.

140
00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:32.290
Now if they're less than 45,

141
00:06:32.290 --> 00:06:33.682
recurrent anovulation

142
00:06:33.682 --> 00:06:36.360
or there's other risk for endometrial cancer,

143
00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:38.558
or I'm concerned because they're over 45,

144
00:06:38.558 --> 00:06:41.160
then they automatically go for an endometrial biopsy.

145
00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:42.570
Now keep in mind here,

146
00:06:42.570 --> 00:06:43.920
why are they going for a biopsy

147
00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:46.170
versus a transvaginal ultrasound?

148
00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:47.130
'Cause we're not talking about

149
00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:49.170
postmenopausal bleeding here.

150
00:06:49.170 --> 00:06:51.960
Transvaginal ultrasound to look for endometrial thickness

151
00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:55.230
is in postmenopausal women, right?

152
00:06:55.230 --> 00:06:56.940
If you're premenopausal,

153
00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:00.030
your endometrial stripe should be thick, right?

154
00:07:00.030 --> 00:07:01.200
Good, good, good, good.

155
00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:03.030
Okay, normal endometrium,

156
00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:05.700
they go on back to the same

157
00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:08.190
medical regimen we had on the previous slide.

158
00:07:08.190 --> 00:07:09.840
Hyperplasia without atypia,

159
00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:11.850
they get treated with a progesterone

160
00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:13.323
and then re-biopsied.

161
00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:16.500
Hyperplasia with atypia or adenocarcinoma.

162
00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:19.450
Of course, they're going to go on for definitive treatment.

163
00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:25.233
Now, why was our patient at low risk for cancer?

164
00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:28.350
All the stuff in red.

165
00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:31.080
Otherwise healthy, non-smoker, no medications,

166
00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:32.880
breastfed, normal BMI,

167
00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:35.283
physical exam is normal, Pap, HPV.

168
00:07:36.690 --> 00:07:39.040
That's why this is a patient specific question.

169
00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:42.000
Now in the context of this,

170
00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.773
the other big common issue is PCOS.

171
00:07:47.910 --> 00:07:50.310
You have to have two of the three of the following.

172
00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:52.500
Hyperandrogenism, ovulatory dysfunction,

173
00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:53.793
and polycystic ovaries.

174
00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:58.710
What you see here is an altered luteinizing hormone.

175
00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:01.050
You see insulin resistance

176
00:08:01.050 --> 00:08:05.490
and this possible predisposition to hyperandrogenism.

177
00:08:05.490 --> 00:08:09.060
We really don't understand why women develop this,

178
00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:11.553
but you need to suspect it if on history.

179
00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:16.800
Abnormal periods, fluctuations in weight,

180
00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:18.660
there are cutaneous findings,

181
00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.240
and you have to ask about common comorbidities.

182
00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:23.490
And what are those?

183
00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:27.600
Metabolic syndrome, obesity, type II diabetes,

184
00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:30.480
non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, sleep apnea.

185
00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:31.680
These women are at increased risk

186
00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:35.220
for cardiovascular disease and for mood disorders.

187
00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:39.870
Now, two of these have to be positive

188
00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:41.460
as we look at the diagnosis.

189
00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:44.040
These are called the Rotterdam criteria.

190
00:08:44.040 --> 00:08:46.053
So you have to have hyperandrogenism.

191
00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:49.650
Clinically, this can be determined

192
00:08:49.650 --> 00:08:51.150
or you can do a chemically?

193
00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:52.623
Either one.

194
00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:56.640
Two, you have to have ovulatory dysfunction.

195
00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:00.630
That can be oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea.

196
00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:03.450
And then if you don't have those two,

197
00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:07.860
then you're going to need to get a ultrasound.

198
00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:11.403
Single ovary is all you need to document this.

199
00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:14.940
Now here's the evaluation.

200
00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:17.250
We exclude pregnancy.

201
00:09:17.250 --> 00:09:20.400
Now we sometimes have to exclude causes

202
00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:23.973
other than PCOS for the hyperandrogenism.

203
00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:26.820
Thyroid disease, prolactin disease,

204
00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:29.553
they could have a 21-hydroxylase deficiency.

205
00:09:30.540 --> 00:09:33.000
Cushings, acromegaly.

206
00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:34.620
You only have to go looking for those

207
00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:36.120
if they have physical findings

208
00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:38.283
that suggest those conditions.

209
00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:42.930
There's no need to get laboratory testing

210
00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:46.143
if they don't have suggestive physical findings.

211
00:09:47.010 --> 00:09:49.184
And then you can document

212
00:09:49.184 --> 00:09:51.870
the biochemical hyperandrogenemia,

213
00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:54.030
total bioavailable or free testosterone,

214
00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:55.470
or you can do DHEA-S.

215
00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:56.943
Any of those can be done.

216
00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:00.030
Now why do they get this insulin resistance?

217
00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:03.063
Of course, this is where insulin sensitivity decreases.

218
00:10:04.830 --> 00:10:06.510
With that, your body says,

219
00:10:06.510 --> 00:10:08.970
well, you need more 'cause it's not working very well.

220
00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:11.010
So you see an insulin release

221
00:10:11.010 --> 00:10:13.443
and circulating insulin increases.

222
00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:16.440
Now unless you have a metabolic syndrome present,

223
00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:18.543
you will see normal glucose tolerance.

224
00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:22.050
The resistance happens when cells in your muscle,

225
00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:24.330
cells in fat, cells in liver

226
00:10:24.330 --> 00:10:27.960
just are not responding to insulin as they should.

227
00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:29.370
This can be a temporary issue.

228
00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:31.260
It can be a chronic issue.

229
00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:33.720
When we are thinking about PCOS,

230
00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:35.250
that insulin resistance

231
00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:38.673
is what stimulates the ovarian androgen production.

232
00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:42.510
That's what leads to the anovulation.

233
00:10:42.510 --> 00:10:44.640
And this prolonged anovulation

234
00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.200
is where you can lead to the development

235
00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:49.383
of these enlarged ovaries with all these cysts.

236
00:10:50.730 --> 00:10:54.528
The hyperinsulinemia along with the hyperandrogenemia,

237
00:10:54.528 --> 00:10:56.040
that is what interferes

238
00:10:56.040 --> 00:10:58.200
with the secretion of the normal gonadotropins

239
00:10:58.200 --> 00:11:00.510
from our pituitary gland.

240
00:11:00.510 --> 00:11:03.360
And that's when we get the change in the LH surge.

241
00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:05.310
And its normal diurnal variation,

242
00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:07.563
which leads to the altered menses.

243
00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:11.100
How do we manage this?

244
00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:15.038
Oligomenorrhea and amenorrhea, OCPs.

245
00:11:15.038 --> 00:11:17.820
Hirsutism, OCPs.

246
00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:20.940
Infertility, clomiphene,

247
00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:23.193
but the better drug is letrozole.

248
00:11:24.750 --> 00:11:28.653
Only use metformin if you have insulin resistance.

249
00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:31.890
I know what everybody thinks,

250
00:11:31.890 --> 00:11:34.563
but the data shows it does not improve fertility.

251
00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:38.340
And then lastly, the weight issue.

252
00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:40.920
That has a positive effect on fertility

253
00:11:40.920 --> 00:11:44.043
and it has a positive effect on your metabolic profile.

254
00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:47.250
Here are key recommendations.

255
00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:49.050
Put those with your study materials.

256
00:11:49.050 --> 00:11:50.850
Here's our next question.

257
00:11:50.850 --> 00:11:52.800
36-year-old G3P2A1 presents

258
00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:54.780
a 14-month history of vein amenorrhea,

259
00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:56.310
hot flashes, and vaginal dryness.

260
00:11:56.310 --> 00:11:57.720
She previously had normal menses

261
00:11:57.720 --> 00:11:59.940
and takes no medications.

262
00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:02.430
Past medical and surgical histories are negative.

263
00:12:02.430 --> 00:12:05.638
Patient is 66 inches tall and her BMI is 23.5.

264
00:12:05.638 --> 00:12:07.500
Her vital signs are normal.

265
00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:08.550
Physical exam is normal.

266
00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:11.220
Laboratory studies reveal a negative pregnancy test.

267
00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:15.333
Normal TSH, prolactin, and elevated LH and FSH levels.

268
00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:18.693
The most likely diagnosis here.

269
00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:21.480
Functional hypothalamic amenorrhea,

270
00:12:21.480 --> 00:12:23.460
intrauterine synechiae,

271
00:12:23.460 --> 00:12:25.953
primary ovarian insufficiency, or Turner's.

272
00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:35.940
Okay, so this is primary ovarian insufficiency.

273
00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:39.810
So as we think about secondary amenorrhea,

274
00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:42.000
it could be PCOS,

275
00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:43.861
but it can be any of these other five

276
00:12:43.861 --> 00:12:45.180
that are listed there.

277
00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:47.100
In practice though,

278
00:12:47.100 --> 00:12:50.550
the most common reason people will be amenorrheic

279
00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:53.490
is there on a progestin only contraceptive,

280
00:12:53.490 --> 00:12:55.170
which is why they like them so much.

281
00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:57.210
Because are you ready for this?

282
00:12:57.210 --> 00:12:58.683
Hold onto your seats.

283
00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:03.990
Funded research has demonstrated

284
00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:06.930
that women prefer fewer periods.

285
00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:08.820
(students laughing)

286
00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:09.653
<v Student>Sorry.</v>

287
00:13:10.890 --> 00:13:13.470
<v ->I mean people got funded</v>

288
00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:14.733
to do that study.

289
00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:18.570
I did it one night at the dinner table.

290
00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:20.874
Hey ladies, what do you think?

291
00:13:20.874 --> 00:13:24.240
Why do we always talk about this stuff at dinner?

292
00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:25.800
Steps in the evaluation here.

293
00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:27.810
Rule out the pregnancy, thyroid disease.

294
00:13:27.810 --> 00:13:31.033
And now I've gotta determine the relative estrogen status

295
00:13:31.033 --> 00:13:33.630
with a progestin challenge test.

296
00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:34.463
How do I do this?

297
00:13:34.463 --> 00:13:35.910
I get five to 10 milligrams

298
00:13:35.910 --> 00:13:38.280
of hydroxy progesterone acetate,

299
00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:40.780
Any bleeding when I withdraw that

300
00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:45.693
even a spot is considered positive.

301
00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:50.880
Now if they have an elevated TSH or prolactin,

302
00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.550
of course they've got hypothyroidism or pituitary disease.

303
00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:54.550
But keep in mind

304
00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:59.220
you are gonna have other stigmata of hypothyroidism

305
00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:03.393
before they present with abnormal periods typically.

306
00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:05.490
The flip side to that

307
00:14:05.490 --> 00:14:08.970
is you're never gonna find a patient with hypothyroidism

308
00:14:08.970 --> 00:14:10.027
who comes in and says,

309
00:14:10.027 --> 00:14:12.657
"I think it's my gland because my weight is up."

310
00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:14.730
Okay, it's impossible.

311
00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.200
It's just not gonna happen.

312
00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:17.730
They're gonna have other findings.

313
00:14:17.730 --> 00:14:19.590
Now, the progestin challenges

314
00:14:19.590 --> 00:14:21.420
those who have a normal TSN chip prolactin.

315
00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:24.750
If they have a withdrawal bleed, I've got anovulation.

316
00:14:24.750 --> 00:14:28.080
Now, anovulatory amenorrhea.

317
00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:31.770
Adequate estrogen, positive progestin challenge.

318
00:14:31.770 --> 00:14:34.260
PCOS is a cause of this.

319
00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:38.130
I don't have progesterone being adequately produced.

320
00:14:38.130 --> 00:14:39.990
Unopposed estrogen stimulation.

321
00:14:39.990 --> 00:14:41.940
My risk of endometrial cancer is up,

322
00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:45.090
and therefore my treatment is typically to use an OCP

323
00:14:45.090 --> 00:14:48.630
or a progestin to help stabilize that endometrium.

324
00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:50.400
Now what about if the TSH is normal,

325
00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:51.510
prolactin is normal,

326
00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:52.860
you do the progestin challenge

327
00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:55.620
and you don't have a withdrawal bleed?

328
00:14:55.620 --> 00:14:57.420
Then I have to give both an estrogen

329
00:14:57.420 --> 00:14:59.133
and progestin challenge.

330
00:15:00.240 --> 00:15:01.620
No withdrawal bleed there.

331
00:15:01.620 --> 00:15:04.420
I'm dealing with some type of outflow tract obstruction.

332
00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:08.670
If I have a withdrawal bleed

333
00:15:08.670 --> 00:15:10.530
following my estrogen and progesterone,

334
00:15:10.530 --> 00:15:12.690
then I'm gonna measure an FSH and LH.

335
00:15:12.690 --> 00:15:13.650
If it's high,

336
00:15:13.650 --> 00:15:15.950
I am gonna have primary ovarian insufficiency.

337
00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:19.860
If it's low or normal, I get an MRI.

338
00:15:19.860 --> 00:15:22.353
If that's normal, I got hypothalamic amenorrhea.

339
00:15:23.820 --> 00:15:25.860
Now with hypothalamic amenorrhea

340
00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:28.863
or hypogonadotropic hypogonadism,

341
00:15:29.910 --> 00:15:31.770
lower normal FSH or LH,

342
00:15:31.770 --> 00:15:34.710
normal prolactin, low levels of endogenous estrogen.

343
00:15:34.710 --> 00:15:37.650
You got a normal MRI of the sella.

344
00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:39.270
They get a positive withdrawal bleed

345
00:15:39.270 --> 00:15:41.970
from the estrogen-progestin challenge.

346
00:15:41.970 --> 00:15:45.540
They typically have anorexia or bulimia,

347
00:15:45.540 --> 00:15:48.180
high levels of stress, high intensity exercise,

348
00:15:48.180 --> 00:15:49.780
or some type of chronic illness.

349
00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:55.080
Here, one of the concerns

350
00:15:55.080 --> 00:15:56.673
is decreased bone density.

351
00:15:57.810 --> 00:16:00.810
We don't know if it's increases the risk of fractures.

352
00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:03.270
You wanna make sure they decrease intensive exercising.

353
00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:04.380
Is that as a cause?

354
00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:05.310
And wouldn't you love this?

355
00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:07.653
Just get that BMI above 20.

356
00:16:09.450 --> 00:16:11.070
Typically, we're not talking with patients about

357
00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:13.023
you need to get your BMI above 20.

358
00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:16.593
Okay, now ovarian failure.

359
00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:20.400
It could be primary.

360
00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:21.780
It could be postmenopausal.

361
00:16:21.780 --> 00:16:24.270
If they have the absence of secondary sex characteristics,

362
00:16:24.270 --> 00:16:25.920
you've got gonadal dysgenesis.

363
00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:27.810
The most common thing we see in the United States,

364
00:16:27.810 --> 00:16:31.473
although not common, is Turner syndrome.

365
00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:34.680
The onset of heavy menses at menarchy

366
00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:36.450
is often the first sign of what disorder?

367
00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:39.783
Hemophilia A, von Willebrand, leukemia or ITP?

368
00:16:45.240 --> 00:16:47.400
Okay, von Willebrand, exactly.

369
00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:49.890
So this gets us to ovulatory

370
00:16:49.890 --> 00:16:51.213
abnormal uterine bleeding.

371
00:16:52.260 --> 00:16:54.360
This is not estrogen driven.

372
00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:57.873
So less than 1% of women develop cancer or hyperplasia.

373
00:16:59.010 --> 00:16:59.843
The differential here

374
00:16:59.843 --> 00:17:01.080
is typically a bleeding disorder.

375
00:17:01.080 --> 00:17:03.166
You could have hypothyroidism, advanced liver disease,

376
00:17:03.166 --> 00:17:05.913
or you could have a structural lesion.

377
00:17:07.050 --> 00:17:09.210
Now here's the evaluation.

378
00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:11.253
Same laboratory tests.

379
00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:13.073
What do we need to do

380
00:17:13.073 --> 00:17:14.730
in terms of looking for a bleeding disorder?

381
00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:17.640
CBC, PT/PTT.

382
00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:20.493
You do not have to do a fibrinogen or thrombin.

383
00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:23.823
You should do this in adolescence,

384
00:17:25.080 --> 00:17:27.690
and in an older woman,

385
00:17:27.690 --> 00:17:29.550
i.e. beyond adolescents,

386
00:17:29.550 --> 00:17:32.850
if they have one or more of the following risk factors.

387
00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:35.430
There's a family history of a bleeding disorder

388
00:17:35.430 --> 00:17:38.670
or my menses are lasting greater than seven days.

389
00:17:38.670 --> 00:17:40.563
It's impairing activities.

390
00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:43.740
There's a history of treatment of anemia,

391
00:17:43.740 --> 00:17:45.781
or I've got a history of excessive bleeding

392
00:17:45.781 --> 00:17:47.880
with things like a tooth extraction

393
00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:49.508
or when I had a delivery

394
00:17:49.508 --> 00:17:53.793
or when I had a termination or some form of surgery.

395
00:17:55.470 --> 00:17:59.373
Now, imaging here, typically this is only done in adult.

396
00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:02.943
Here, this is where we start with imaging.

397
00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:06.120
You do not wanna start with imaging

398
00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:08.673
if you think that this is an ovulatory.

399
00:18:09.600 --> 00:18:12.540
You start with imaging when it's ovulatory,

400
00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:14.460
'cause it could be a structural defect.

401
00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:15.600
If that's normal,

402
00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:17.280
then they get an endometrial biopsy.

403
00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:20.073
Same exact age cutoffs.

404
00:18:22.350 --> 00:18:24.750
Now, if we evaluate for the bleeding disorder,

405
00:18:24.750 --> 00:18:25.830
we've got a bleeding disorder,

406
00:18:25.830 --> 00:18:27.930
that goes off to be treated.

407
00:18:27.930 --> 00:18:29.820
The imaging is normal.

408
00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:31.863
I get a endometrial biopsy.

409
00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:36.150
Now, if I find on my imaging I've got a fibroid,

410
00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:37.590
that can be fixed.

411
00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:39.510
Polyp, refer.

412
00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:41.130
Normal imaging results,

413
00:18:41.130 --> 00:18:42.840
we go back to the same medical treatment

414
00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:44.493
we had for anovulatory.

415
00:18:48.390 --> 00:18:49.980
So here's a summary of treatment

416
00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:51.430
of abnormal uterine bleeding.

417
00:18:52.641 --> 00:18:55.890
Medically, sometimes it needs to be done surgically,

418
00:18:55.890 --> 00:18:59.760
myomectomy, hysterectomy, ablation.

419
00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:01.830
As we look at these,

420
00:19:01.830 --> 00:19:04.470
surgery, hysterectomy reduces menstrual bleeding

421
00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:06.570
more than medical treatment at one year.

422
00:19:06.570 --> 00:19:07.593
Not surprising.

423
00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:10.230
Oral medication tends to suit

424
00:19:10.230 --> 00:19:13.020
a minority of women in the long term.

425
00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:14.973
A levonorgestrel intrauterine system

426
00:19:14.973 --> 00:19:17.790
is actually FDA approved

427
00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:21.390
to treat abnormal uterine bleeding.

428
00:19:21.390 --> 00:19:23.670
It's a better alternative to surgery.

429
00:19:23.670 --> 00:19:25.560
One study showed that 69% of women

430
00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:26.910
who were scheduled for a hysterectomy

431
00:19:26.910 --> 00:19:28.770
when they had the intrauterine system put in

432
00:19:28.770 --> 00:19:30.063
canceled their surgery.

433
00:19:31.110 --> 00:19:33.150
Both are safe and effective.

434
00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:35.070
Here are sort recommendations related to that.

435
00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:37.650
You can put those with your study folder.

436
00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:39.393
Perimenopausal bleeding.

437
00:19:40.230 --> 00:19:42.120
The endometrial biopsy is done on risk

438
00:19:42.120 --> 00:19:44.280
as we've already looked at.

439
00:19:44.280 --> 00:19:47.370
We can treat it with progestins OCPs.

440
00:19:47.370 --> 00:19:49.050
This is a place in my practice

441
00:19:49.050 --> 00:19:51.273
where I use low dose OCPs a lot.

442
00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:54.960
You can use the levonorgestrel intrauterine system,

443
00:19:54.960 --> 00:19:57.123
or you can put 'em on hormone therapy.

444
00:19:58.110 --> 00:20:00.420
So if they're having hot flashes,

445
00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:03.549
you could use this in terms of hormone therapy,

446
00:20:03.549 --> 00:20:07.080
which is a much lower dose of estrogen and progesterone

447
00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:09.573
than having them on a combined OCP.

448
00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:12.900
The hormone therapy here,

449
00:20:12.900 --> 00:20:15.450
you tend to do better with sequential

450
00:20:15.450 --> 00:20:18.510
so that you're typically giving 21 days of estrogen

451
00:20:18.510 --> 00:20:22.260
and then 14 days of progesterone at the last 14 days,

452
00:20:22.260 --> 00:20:24.903
as opposed to putting them on continuous.

453
00:20:25.770 --> 00:20:27.480
This will prevent hyperplasia,

454
00:20:27.480 --> 00:20:28.740
but you don't have contraception

455
00:20:28.740 --> 00:20:30.183
'cause it's such a low dose.

456
00:20:31.620 --> 00:20:33.063
Here's choosing wisely.

457
00:20:34.080 --> 00:20:36.810
Do not obtain a FSH level in women in their 40s

458
00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:38.490
to identify the menopausal transition

459
00:20:38.490 --> 00:20:39.990
as the cause of irregular

460
00:20:39.990 --> 00:20:41.853
or abnormal menstrual bleeding.

461
00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:47.520
Next question.

462
00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:49.290
55-year-old postmenopausal woman

463
00:20:49.290 --> 00:20:52.770
presents with two days of vaginal bleeding or spotting.

464
00:20:52.770 --> 00:20:54.930
She initiated hormone therapy 10 months ago

465
00:20:54.930 --> 00:20:57.480
because of significant nocturnal hot flashes.

466
00:20:57.480 --> 00:21:00.780
Which one of the following statements is most accurate?

467
00:21:00.780 --> 00:21:03.933
Vaginal bleeding is uncommon after HT is initiated;

468
00:21:04.890 --> 00:21:06.780
more than 40% of females experience

469
00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:08.433
vaginal bleeding after menopause;

470
00:21:09.330 --> 00:21:10.890
transvaginal ultrasound is appropriate

471
00:21:10.890 --> 00:21:11.940
for the initial evaluation

472
00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:13.980
of postmenopausal bleeding;

473
00:21:13.980 --> 00:21:15.180
the most common cause

474
00:21:15.180 --> 00:21:18.633
of postmenopausal bleeding is fibroids.

475
00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:26.220
So transvaginal ultrasound

476
00:21:26.220 --> 00:21:29.460
is the appropriate initial evaluation

477
00:21:29.460 --> 00:21:31.260
for postmenopausal bleeding.

478
00:21:31.260 --> 00:21:32.297
Now if we're thinking about

479
00:21:32.297 --> 00:21:33.514
the differential diagnosis here,

480
00:21:33.514 --> 00:21:35.190
the most common reason

481
00:21:35.190 --> 00:21:38.700
for postmenopausal bleeding is polyps actually, polyps.

482
00:21:38.700 --> 00:21:41.730
This gets us to a brief discussion of cancers.

483
00:21:41.730 --> 00:21:42.563
Keep in mind,

484
00:21:42.563 --> 00:21:44.340
here are the key facts on endometrial cancer.

485
00:21:44.340 --> 00:21:46.773
It's the most common gynecologic malignancy.

486
00:21:47.850 --> 00:21:51.480
85% of women with endometrial cancer will present

487
00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:54.723
with abnormal uterine bleeding postmenopausally.

488
00:21:56.430 --> 00:21:58.957
85% of postmenopausal bleeding

489
00:21:58.957 --> 00:22:01.293
is not endometrial cancer.

490
00:22:02.220 --> 00:22:03.690
Think about that for a moment.

491
00:22:03.690 --> 00:22:05.190
No screening test.

492
00:22:05.190 --> 00:22:07.560
Strongest association with reduced risk.

493
00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:09.120
Combined hormonal contraception,

494
00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:10.541
50% reduction in risk.

495
00:22:10.541 --> 00:22:12.210
The protection lasts

496
00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:14.670
up to 15 years after discontinuation.

497
00:22:14.670 --> 00:22:17.580
The driver for most of this is estrogen.

498
00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:21.120
So any question where they're older,

499
00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:23.580
nulliparity, history of infertility,

500
00:22:23.580 --> 00:22:26.696
all anything that's gonna drive estrogen persistence

501
00:22:26.696 --> 00:22:30.090
is what's going to be the risk factor here.

502
00:22:30.090 --> 00:22:31.320
Transvaginal ultrasound

503
00:22:31.320 --> 00:22:32.580
is how this should be evaluated.

504
00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:34.410
Since we don't have a screening test,

505
00:22:34.410 --> 00:22:36.570
the important thing to remind postmenopausal women

506
00:22:36.570 --> 00:22:41.570
is any bleeding, even a spot, I need to know about.

507
00:22:43.110 --> 00:22:44.490
Dr. Weismiller, you wanna hear just about

508
00:22:44.490 --> 00:22:45.323
a spot of bleeding?

509
00:22:45.323 --> 00:22:46.710
Yes, call me at home.

510
00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:47.810
I wanna know about it.

511
00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:50.253
Very important.

512
00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:53.070
Okay, here are the practice recommendations

513
00:22:53.070 --> 00:22:54.971
for that, endometrial cancer.

514
00:22:54.971 --> 00:22:56.190
Ovarian cancer.

515
00:22:56.190 --> 00:22:58.500
This is the most lethal.

516
00:22:58.500 --> 00:23:01.023
Highest risk factor: genetic predisposition.

517
00:23:01.890 --> 00:23:03.480
We don't have a screening test.

518
00:23:03.480 --> 00:23:06.453
The Ca-125 is used to monitor.

519
00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:10.166
Increased risk: estrogen,

520
00:23:10.166 --> 00:23:12.810
genetic syndromes, obesity.

521
00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:17.133
Decreased risk, breastfeeding, OCP use, Depo.

522
00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:24.099
Prevention, besides OCPs and DMPA or Depo,

523
00:23:24.099 --> 00:23:27.060
breastfeeding, tubal sterilization,

524
00:23:27.060 --> 00:23:28.530
what we call an opportunistic salpingectomy.

525
00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:31.113
'Cause as we said earlier in the week,

526
00:23:32.760 --> 00:23:35.280
the ovarian cancer arises from the tube,

527
00:23:35.280 --> 00:23:36.723
not from the ovary.

528
00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:41.103
Screening, we don't have one.

529
00:23:42.780 --> 00:23:44.670
High risk family history,

530
00:23:44.670 --> 00:23:46.830
you can offer a referral for genetic counseling

531
00:23:46.830 --> 00:23:49.440
the same way we did breast cancer.

532
00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.720
Hello, does anybody in the family have breast,

533
00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:54.063
ovarian, peritoneal, or tubal cancer?

534
00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:57.750
There's the clinical recommendations

535
00:23:57.750 --> 00:23:59.010
based on ovarian cancer

536
00:23:59.010 --> 00:24:00.780
and we go to cervical cancer,

537
00:24:00.780 --> 00:24:04.923
which is an STD caused by an STI.

538
00:24:08.910 --> 00:24:11.788
The only other risk factor associated independently

539
00:24:11.788 --> 00:24:15.603
with cervical cancer is smoking.

540
00:24:16.530 --> 00:24:19.083
Here's the current recommendation for screening.

541
00:24:19.980 --> 00:24:21.850
Cytology alone every three years

542
00:24:22.722 --> 00:24:24.960
between the ages of 21 and 65,

543
00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:28.590
or from 30 to 65

544
00:24:28.590 --> 00:24:33.590
HPV testing plus cytology or primary HPV testing.

545
00:24:35.550 --> 00:24:37.290
Now the American Cancer Society

546
00:24:37.290 --> 00:24:38.970
has already moved to a recommendation

547
00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:40.500
of primary HPV testing

548
00:24:40.500 --> 00:24:42.700
and they don't start screening until age 25.

549
00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:46.380
The USPSTF is looking at this right now.

550
00:24:46.380 --> 00:24:48.480
They're gonna move it to 25 too, I'm sure.

551
00:24:49.500 --> 00:24:51.480
When the most recent consensus guidelines

552
00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:53.550
were published way back in 2012,

553
00:24:53.550 --> 00:24:54.840
the consensus panel said

554
00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:56.580
the data all supports not screening

555
00:24:56.580 --> 00:24:59.040
for cervical cancer until age 25.

556
00:24:59.040 --> 00:25:01.263
We feel uncomfortable with that.

557
00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:07.563
Okay, under 25, the ACS says, do not screen.

558
00:25:09.330 --> 00:25:12.393
Over 65, do not screen.

559
00:25:13.320 --> 00:25:16.650
Hysterectomy with removal of the cervix.

560
00:25:16.650 --> 00:25:18.540
Somebody asked yesterday,

561
00:25:18.540 --> 00:25:19.380
if the patient doesn't know

562
00:25:19.380 --> 00:25:21.447
if they had their cervix removed,

563
00:25:21.447 --> 00:25:22.280
how do we find out?

564
00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:25.410
No, you do a physical exam

565
00:25:25.410 --> 00:25:29.670
and you look for it or you feel for it, okay?

566
00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:32.730
But if they've had removal of the cervix,

567
00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:35.073
you do not do a Pap.

568
00:25:35.910 --> 00:25:37.980
Even if the cervix was removed

569
00:25:37.980 --> 00:25:39.990
because they had endometrial cancer,

570
00:25:39.990 --> 00:25:42.930
you do not do a Pap.

571
00:25:42.930 --> 00:25:44.913
No screening for cervical cancer.

572
00:25:48.180 --> 00:25:50.307
Now, if you're doing primary HPV screening,

573
00:25:50.307 --> 00:25:51.480
this is how it's done.

574
00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:53.220
You collect it just like you would

575
00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:54.813
if you were doing cytology.

576
00:25:55.860 --> 00:25:57.480
If it comes back type 16 or 18,

577
00:25:57.480 --> 00:25:59.010
they go directly for colposcopy.

578
00:25:59.010 --> 00:26:01.350
If it's one of the other 12 high risk types

579
00:26:01.350 --> 00:26:03.540
that are detected in the cobas test,

580
00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:04.847
cytology is then done.

581
00:26:04.847 --> 00:26:07.980
They just go pull out that vial that you sent them.

582
00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:09.690
If it's negative, they go to routine screening

583
00:26:09.690 --> 00:26:10.990
every three to five years.

584
00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:15.420
Now, in terms of follow-up now,

585
00:26:15.420 --> 00:26:16.530
I don't think you're gonna have a question

586
00:26:16.530 --> 00:26:17.363
on the exam on this

587
00:26:17.363 --> 00:26:19.530
because now the newest guidelines

588
00:26:19.530 --> 00:26:23.043
looking at management of abnormalities is risk-based.

589
00:26:24.030 --> 00:26:26.490
So it's not just, oh, I had this with the last one.

590
00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:27.690
That's where I'm going.

591
00:26:27.690 --> 00:26:30.090
So I think knowing the screening

592
00:26:30.090 --> 00:26:31.803
is the most important thing here.

593
00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:35.070
How do we prevent this?

594
00:26:35.070 --> 00:26:39.303
Condoms, quit smoking and immunize.

595
00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:43.200
The non-valent human papillomavirus vaccine

596
00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:44.550
prevents genital warts.

597
00:26:44.550 --> 00:26:46.740
It prevents cervical and anal cancers,

598
00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:50.490
penile cancer, and hopefully head and neck cancer.

599
00:26:50.490 --> 00:26:51.750
There's a large study going on now

600
00:26:51.750 --> 00:26:53.370
because we now have more head and neck cancer,

601
00:26:53.370 --> 00:26:55.110
secondary HPV in the US

602
00:26:55.110 --> 00:26:57.390
than we do cervical cancer,

603
00:26:57.390 --> 00:26:58.590
and most of it's in men.

604
00:26:59.970 --> 00:27:02.400
I saw a patient within the last two weeks

605
00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:05.010
recently diagnosed with a HPV positive

606
00:27:05.010 --> 00:27:06.603
head and neck cancer, 53.

607
00:27:07.440 --> 00:27:11.310
Okay, who gets a pelvic exam?

608
00:27:11.310 --> 00:27:12.363
Who knows?

609
00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:14.850
If you're symptomatic with something,

610
00:27:14.850 --> 00:27:16.143
you get a pelvic exam.

611
00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:18.780
But otherwise, the most recent review

612
00:27:18.780 --> 00:27:20.850
of the literature by the USPSTF

613
00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:23.463
says it's a category I as to how often you do it.

614
00:27:27.390 --> 00:27:29.100
Menopause, the two big issues

615
00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:33.360
are vasomotor instability and atrophic vaginitis.

616
00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:37.380
About 85% of women will experience vasomotor symptoms.

617
00:27:37.380 --> 00:27:39.963
90% of them will bring it up to the doctor.

618
00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:42.370
We don't bring it up to them.

619
00:27:43.950 --> 00:27:45.497
And of the majority of women

620
00:27:45.497 --> 00:27:47.550
who would benefit from treatment,

621
00:27:47.550 --> 00:27:49.353
60% never get treated.

622
00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:51.750
Very sad state.

623
00:27:51.750 --> 00:27:53.610
How do we treat?

624
00:27:53.610 --> 00:27:56.700
We do an estrogen containing hormone therapy.

625
00:27:56.700 --> 00:27:58.770
There are non-hormonal medications.

626
00:27:58.770 --> 00:28:00.390
There's non-pharmacologic.

627
00:28:00.390 --> 00:28:02.820
The non-pharmacologic, CBT and hypnosis.

628
00:28:02.820 --> 00:28:04.970
They're effective for short-term reduction.

629
00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:13.310
Other issues, herbal, botanical, exercise,

630
00:28:13.860 --> 00:28:17.220
tai chi, acupuncture.

631
00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:20.370
The data says they don't work for vasomotor symptoms.

632
00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:22.140
If they work for your patient, fine.

633
00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:25.320
But they don't work in terms of large studies.

634
00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:29.103
Systemic hormone therapy is the most effective.

635
00:28:30.750 --> 00:28:33.840
Use whatever vehicle to deliver it as you want.

636
00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:36.030
What is not effective for vasomotor symptoms?

637
00:28:36.030 --> 00:28:39.270
Progesterone only medications, testosterone alone,

638
00:28:39.270 --> 00:28:42.243
or compounded bioidentical hormones?

639
00:28:43.230 --> 00:28:45.360
The North American Menopause Society,

640
00:28:45.360 --> 00:28:48.300
most effective treatment for vasomotor symptoms

641
00:28:48.300 --> 00:28:52.380
and genital urinate symptoms is hormone therapy.

642
00:28:52.380 --> 00:28:54.060
It's been shown to prevent bone loss.

643
00:28:54.060 --> 00:28:55.470
We know that.

644
00:28:55.470 --> 00:28:59.820
The risk depend on my age, vehicle used, et cetera,

645
00:28:59.820 --> 00:29:02.403
and you always have to individualize this.

646
00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:05.820
The systemic formulations

647
00:29:05.820 --> 00:29:08.790
of which there's only one transdermal systemic,

648
00:29:08.790 --> 00:29:10.800
these are typically gonna be preferred

649
00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:11.880
for vasomotor symptoms.

650
00:29:11.880 --> 00:29:13.530
Vaginal estrogen formulations,

651
00:29:13.530 --> 00:29:15.030
these are minimally absorbed.

652
00:29:15.030 --> 00:29:17.700
They're gonna be used for atrophic vaginitis.

653
00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:19.680
Now, here's the scoop.

654
00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:22.380
If you're younger and within 10 years of menopause,

655
00:29:22.380 --> 00:29:25.650
the benefit outweighs the risk of hormone therapy.

656
00:29:25.650 --> 00:29:26.640
If you're older,

657
00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:30.300
over 60 or more than 10 years since menopause,

658
00:29:30.300 --> 00:29:32.523
the risk outweighs the benefit.

659
00:29:34.470 --> 00:29:38.283
There is no age by definition to stop this.

660
00:29:39.990 --> 00:29:43.770
If they're benefiting, you can continue.

661
00:29:43.770 --> 00:29:45.330
In my practice at two years,

662
00:29:45.330 --> 00:29:47.670
we typically start having a discussion annually.

663
00:29:47.670 --> 00:29:49.650
I got patients in their 70s

664
00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:51.603
still on hormone therapy.

665
00:29:52.950 --> 00:29:55.470
Contraindications, I've got unexplained vaginal bleeding.

666
00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:57.510
There's a history of a stroke,

667
00:29:57.510 --> 00:29:59.790
history of thromboembolism.

668
00:29:59.790 --> 00:30:03.960
Testosterone alone does not help vasomotor symptoms.

669
00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:06.240
If you combine it with HT

670
00:30:06.240 --> 00:30:08.160
because they have vasomotor symptoms,

671
00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:09.720
which is the only indication

672
00:30:09.720 --> 00:30:11.490
for systemic hormone therapy,

673
00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:13.380
you see improved sexual function scores

674
00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:16.383
and improved number of sexually satisfying experiences.

675
00:30:17.910 --> 00:30:21.360
Here are our practice recommendations.

676
00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:24.090
And lastly, atrophic vaginitis.

677
00:30:24.090 --> 00:30:25.770
What's important here?

678
00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:28.440
The urinary symptoms look just like a UTI,

679
00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:30.810
including what you will see on the UA.

680
00:30:30.810 --> 00:30:31.783
I'm here, Dr. Weismiller,

681
00:30:31.783 --> 00:30:34.020
I got another urinary tract infection.

682
00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:35.220
Never met the patient.

683
00:30:35.220 --> 00:30:36.120
I look at the chart.

684
00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:37.470
They've had four urine cultures.

685
00:30:37.470 --> 00:30:39.000
They're all negative.

686
00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:42.180
You've never had a urinary tract infection, what?

687
00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:43.680
Do you have any vaginal dryness?

688
00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:46.200
Oh my gosh, it's dry like the Sahara.

689
00:30:46.200 --> 00:30:47.970
Yeah, painful urination,

690
00:30:47.970 --> 00:30:50.013
blood in the urine, increased frequency.

691
00:30:51.210 --> 00:30:53.853
Moisturizers and lubricants are first line.

692
00:30:55.170 --> 00:30:58.530
Vaginal estrogen is then added.

693
00:30:58.530 --> 00:31:00.120
Typically, you're not going to need

694
00:31:00.120 --> 00:31:01.350
to add any progesterone

695
00:31:01.350 --> 00:31:04.890
because they don't have systemic reactions.

696
00:31:04.890 --> 00:31:07.980
Non-pharmacologic is not sufficient,

697
00:31:07.980 --> 00:31:10.620
and I'm not touching down there

698
00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:12.965
or I can't get there.

699
00:31:12.965 --> 00:31:14.610
Ospemifene is a serum

700
00:31:14.610 --> 00:31:18.030
that acts as an estrogen agonist in the vagina

701
00:31:18.030 --> 00:31:20.340
has no clinically significant effect

702
00:31:20.340 --> 00:31:23.280
on the endometrium or breast, so that could be used.

703
00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:24.780
If you have a history of breast cancer,

704
00:31:24.780 --> 00:31:27.300
which is estrogen receptor positive of course,

705
00:31:27.300 --> 00:31:31.140
those patients, even if there's a low risk of recurrence,

706
00:31:31.140 --> 00:31:33.300
no estrogen systemically,

707
00:31:33.300 --> 00:31:35.460
maybe a low dose estrogen vaginally,

708
00:31:35.460 --> 00:31:37.350
but you're gonna have to talk with your oncologist

709
00:31:37.350 --> 00:31:38.790
and the patient together.

710
00:31:38.790 --> 00:31:40.710
Those are our practice recommendations.

711
00:31:40.710 --> 00:31:42.090
Please keep in mind

712
00:31:42.090 --> 00:31:43.740
if they give you a question

713
00:31:43.740 --> 00:31:46.860
where they're on a vaginal estrogen preparation

714
00:31:46.860 --> 00:31:48.900
and they have postmenopausal bleeding,

715
00:31:48.900 --> 00:31:51.423
you still have to evaluate the endometrium.

716
00:31:53.190 --> 00:31:56.070
Okay, those are our sore recommendations,

717
00:31:56.070 --> 00:31:57.600
and we are done.

718
00:31:57.600 --> 00:31:59.051
Thank you very much.

719
00:31:59.051 --> 00:32:01.438
(audiences applauding)

720
00:32:01.438 --> 00:32:04.521
(light bright music)

